"Szpunar G., Aloise G., Mazzotti S., Nieder L., Cristaldi M.","Effects of global climate change on terrestrial small mammal communities in Italy",2008,"Fresenius Environmental Bulletin","17","9 B",,"1526","1533",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-55549119306&partnerID=40&md5=eaf002c644faeef2ac1fd51984e252f1","Department of Animal and Human Biology, Sapienza University of Rome, Via Alfonso Borelli 50, 00161 Rome, Italy; Department of Ecology, University of Calabria, Via Pietro Bucci, 87036 Rende (Cosenza), Italy; Museum of Natural History, Via Filippo De' Pisis 24, 44100 Ferrara, Italy; Department of Functional and Evolutive Biology, University of Parma, Viale delle Scienze, 43100 Parma, Italy","Szpunar, G., Department of Animal and Human Biology, Sapienza University of Rome, Via Alfonso Borelli 50, 00161 Rome, Italy; Aloise, G., Department of Ecology, University of Calabria, Via Pietro Bucci, 87036 Rende (Cosenza), Italy; Mazzotti, S., Museum of Natural History, Via Filippo De' Pisis 24, 44100 Ferrara, Italy; Nieder, L., Department of Functional and Evolutive Biology, University of Parma, Viale delle Scienze, 43100 Parma, Italy; Cristaldi, M., Department of Animal and Human Biology, Sapienza University of Rome, Via Alfonso Borelli 50, 00161 Rome, Italy","In the framework of climate change, it has been predicted that the Mediterranean Basin will experience the greatest loss of biodiversity, because it will be heavily affected by several drivers of change. In particular, Italy is an important geographical area because it represents a key hot-spot of biodiversity. The aim of this study was to evaluate the effects of global climate change on terrestrial small mammals (Rodents and Soricomorphs) in Italy. Barn owl (Tyto alba) pellet analysis was applied to study the temporal variations of microteriocoenoses structure. We revisited 21 roosting sites which had been previously studied by other authors and we carried out a similar study in order to analyse possible changes in small mammal communities. Analyses covered a period of about 30 years and the gap between the first and second sampling ranges from 11 to 33 years. Collecting localities were grouped according to the Bioclimatic Map of Italy. Several ecological indexes were applied and their changes through time were analysed for each Bioclimatic Region. Results show a significant increase in thermoxerophilic species in the last thirty years, particularly in the Mediterranean Region. This observed rise is likely due to global and local warming. In fact, higher temperatures, lower precipitation and increasing xerothermic conditions could have facilitated the spread of thermoxerophilic species. The persistence of such a trend could lead to a series of serious ecological consequences in the future, including a possible reduction in biodiversity.","Barn owl pellet analysis; Global warming; Italy; Small mammal communities","bioclimatology; biodiversity; climate change; climate effect; community response; community structure; global climate; global warming; small mammal; temporal variation; Eurasia; Europe; Italy; Southern Europe; Mammalia; Rodentia; Soricomorpha; Strigiformes; Tyto alba; Tytonidae",,,,,,"IPCC (2007). Climate Change 2007. The Physical Science Basis. Cambridge University Press, UK, 996 ppRoot, T.L., Price, J.T., Hall, K.R., Schneider, S.H., Rosenzwel, G.C., Pounds, J.A., Fingerprints of global warming on wild animal and plants (2003) Nature, 421, pp. 57-60; Sala, O., Chapin III, F.S., Armesto, J.J., Berlow, E., Bloomfield, J., Dirzo, R., Huber-Sanwald, E., Wall, D.H., Global Biodiversity Scenarios for the Year 2100 (2000) Science, 287, pp. 1770-1774; Myers, N., Mittermeier, R.A., Mittermeier, C.G., da Fonseca, G.A.B., Kent, J., Biodiversity hotspols for conservation priorities (2000) Nature, 403, pp. 853-858; Bilton, D.T., Mirol, P.M., Mascheretti, S., Fredga, K., Zima, J., Searle, J.B., Mediterranean Europe as an area of endemism for small mammals rat